In the case of
an ornithological collection like Bradley Martin, there's no question that every effort should have been made to have kept it intact.

we would have handled the high spot sale first bringing in a lot of money up front just as we did with Doheny One and then we would have held the bird collection until the end of the series

Christie's London.
My father, my grandfather, and my great-grandfather were in the Red Book business.
And my grandfather and my father were directors of Pickering and Chateau.
My father died in 1980, and William Reece-Mogg bought Pickering and Chateau in 1981.
My uncle is the only surviving partner left and he lives in retirement in Ireland.
I joined Christie's full time in August 1964 in London, remained with them until March 1975 and I came straight over here.
Been with them now for 27 years.
I started coming over here on business trips from London in 1969, 70, 71, 72, not 73, then in 74.
So I've been in contact with this country steadily for 22 years on business.
And I used to do a lot of business with the dealers every year.
Before we get back to Texas, so you've actually been able to observe for 22 years from this vantage point of the action, so to speak.
I've observed the American action, sure, but not in great detail.
I mean, I was 23 when I first came over here, but I certainly, yeah.
Well, the dealers I was closest to when I came over here were Mike Papantonio.
who was a great, great friend of my father, because they dealt in the same kind of hook.
They had a kind of rapport, and my father represented Seven Gables at Auckland.
I met Bart when I first came over here in 1969.
Mike gave Bart $10 out of the till and said, take Stephen out for a night on the town.
And we went down to the Whitehorse Tavern.
And, you know, he...
That was 69, so I've never brought that long.
Is the action still here?
Or has it really shifted as people... Different kinds of action for different places.
I mean, there's no doubt in my mind of the strength of the London market, for example, for a bullish and aggressive trade in the colour plate market and the...

We had...

We proposed this at the same time very much aware that
that we were involving ourselves, and we knew, we said, heavens above, maybe we're backing the wrong horse here.

because he actually got to know Arthur Houghton and thought he was a little crazy.

to those open coffees coming back again, and other things that Haven had put in as well.

The Yates notebook, this kind of thing.

into a great collector dominating the scene for a much longer period of time than somebody like Manny or George Abrams.

The chronology of this is then that

As a show-off.

which was an air of mystery that Haven always liked to cultivate.

our appraisal was going to be accepted as value by both parties.

Probably.

The appraisal would have been.
I haven't any idea.
I can't say, because you don't know what another appraisal is going to be.
Yeah.
Well, his value is value, I think.

One person values things different from another.

I'd say ten million.
Nine.

They wrote a large check in advance.

So therefore, I'm saying, well, I understand, but we could certainly compete with him.
Couldn't we?
because we weren't holding them together.
Yeah, that's right.

You see?

It was company policy.
I'm not saying that there have not been exceptions prior to 1989.
When we've not given an answer, I'm not saying that at all.
What I'm saying is that we have always done second to our competitors when it came to inventive money matters.
And it's no coincidence, therefore,
that we were not approached by Richard Manning for the sale of these things and also I have heard from someone that he still owes money on the failure.

for Audubon's Birds of America.
In November 1977, we beat our own world record with another copy of Audubon's Birds of America for $360,000.

Paid for the Corn Leary Declaration of Independence at Freemans in 1969.

which nobody had ever done before.

and with a block that made 2.2 million.

Morgan.

All of these great sales have basically come on your watch.

Did you have any, speaking of two Gutenbergs, one of which was the Doheny,

Stay on.

Yes.
